('2008-04-19', '06:04:00', 871, 'Blackbird (Turdus merula)', '4 male blackbirds posturing and some fighting on the garage roof. This went on for about 10 minutes from 7.30pm when it was getting quite dark. 2 of them continued until about 7.50pm.', 'Alive', '2', -1.601879597, 54.98895371, 'gardener'),
('2008-04-20', '04:04:00', 531, 'Barn Owl (Tyto alba)', 'Hunting.', 'Alive', '2', -1.872396469, 55.1688192, 'Tim Lamb'),
('2008-04-20', '07:04:00', 1596, 'Chaffinch (Fringilla coelebs)', '4 birds flying together across the allotment, stopping in an elder tree. Too far away to tell if they were male or female, but the white flashes on the wings and characteristic flight pattern identified them as Chaffinch.', 'Alive', '2', -1.61318779, 54.99086187, 'gardener'),
('2008-04-20', '07:04:00', 776, 'Black-billed Magpie (Pica pica)', 'One bird in the middle silver birch tree along the southern allotment hedge. Flew off towards the cemetery.', 'Alive', '2', -1.613273621, 54.99012939, 'gardener'),
('2008-04-20', '07:04:00', 1820, 'Coal Tit (Periparus ater)', 'One bird foraging in the litter at the bottom of the hedge. Flew up into a small tree near to the hedge.', 'Alive', '2', -1.613423824, 54.98657761, 'gardener'),
('2008-04-20', '07:04:00', 871, 'Blackbird (Turdus merula)', '3 female blackbirds that seemed to be sorting out a &#39;pecking order&#39;. They were on the 7ft high brick walls and gently sloping slate roof of the extension and garage chasing each other, running towards each other and pecking, but not doing any of the flying vertically into the air fighting that is seen in males. The obviously dominant female was an extremely battered specimen with a lot of her tail missing and bald patches on her left breast and head. She also had some nesting material (dried grass) clutched in her beak throughout. She was able to fly well despite the feather loss. She sorted out the other 2 females, then flew off. The remaining 2 continued with some minor posturing but there was no obvious winner. This is the first time I&#39;ve seen female blackbirds doing this, although male blackbirds frequently use the walls and roofs in our backyard to fight.', 'Alive', '2', -1.601901054, 54.98895986, 'gardener'),
('2008-04-20', '07:04:00', 990, 'Blue Tit (Cyanistes caeruleus)', '2 blue tits continuing to fly into one of the many nesting boxes in the back yard. No fighting with house sparrows now the bird feeder has been moved. There are a total of 9 nesting boxes available, but non has ever been used although they are checked out by tits and sparrows every year - obviously something is not to their liking. This nesting box is the one that was used by a bumble bee colony for breeding last year. It is the only one facing east. The blue tits have been in and out of the box about 10 times from 6.15-7.15 am, but not seen with any nesting material. Now one of them is pecking at the entrance hole to the box. All plans to move the nesting boxes to the east and west facing garden walls are on hold until we know if we are finally to get birds nesting in the back yard', 'Alive', '2', -1.601901054, 54.98895986, 'gardener'),
('2008-04-20', '07:04:00', 2072, 'Common Starling (Sturnus vulgaris)', '2 starlings on the east wall. We used to get large groups, including youngsters, visiting the back yard, but since we changed to a type of birdfeeder that the pigeons couldn&#39;t use, they don&#39;t visit in such large numbers.', 'Alive', '2', -1.601901054, 54.98895986, 'gardener'),
('2008-04-21', '11:04:00', 8048, 'Sky Lark (Alauda arvensis)', 'Perched on the grass at the edge of the path', 'Alive', '2', -1.624560356, 54.99157586, 'Naomi'),
('2008-04-22', '08:04:00', 8412, 'Song Thrush (Turdus philomelos)', '1 song thrush. Flew in and started foraging on manure heap and then moved to grass next to heap. I was fairly certain is wasn&#39;t the more common mistle thrush, but I wanted to see the orange patch under it&#39;s wing for confirmation, so I started slowly walking towards it and it did fly off over the cemetery road, giving me a good view of it&#39;s underwings.', 'Alive', '2', -1.612286568, 54.99023403, 'gardener'),
('2008-04-22', '08:04:00', 1951, 'Common Frog (Rana temporaria)', '1 young frog in the long grass to the south of the pond. It was about 3cm long with back legs tucked in. Green colour with brown rings in 2 lines down it&#39;s back. Looked healthy', 'Alive', '2', -1.612501144, 54.99021556, 'gardener'),
('2008-04-22', '09:04:00', 3818, 'Great Tit (Parus major)', 'One great tit flew across the back yard, pausing briefly in the elder tree.', 'Alive', '2', -1.601879597, 54.98898448, 'gardener'),
('2008-04-22', '09:04:00', 1820, 'Coal Tit (Periparus ater)', '2 coal tits feeding in a silver birch tree - pecking at something (?buds) on the finest twigs on the tree.', 'Alive', '2', -1.601986885, 54.98936612, 'gardener'),
('2008-04-22', '09:04:00', 990, 'Blue Tit (Cyanistes caeruleus)', '2 blue tits carrying nesting material into the nestbox - seem to do it most frequently early in the morning. Been doing it for 3 days now.', 'Alive', '2', -1.601879597, 54.98898448, 'gardener'),
('2008-04-22', '09:04:00', 1951, 'Common Frog (Rana temporaria)', 'The tadpoles have now all emerged from the frog spawn and some are swimming freely throughout the pond. There is a closely packed row of them each side of a plant stem nibbling away at it.', 'Alive', '2', -1.612415314, 54.99025865, 'gardener'),
('2008-04-22', '09:04:00', 7193, 'Robin (Erithacus rubecula)', '2 different robins visited the plot. One (? female) had ruffled feathers on her back towards her tail and she was more timid. The other robin may have been the one that appeared frequently when I was gardening last year. He perches very close to me on something raised off the ground and chatters loudly at me until I move a little away from where I&#39;m digging so he can move in and grab any bugs and grubs I&#39;ve uncovered. Today he managed to fly off with a huge worm.', 'Alive', '2', -1.612372398, 54.99023403, 'gardener'),
